<sect2 id="tags-and-math-symbols">
<title>LaTeX Tags and Mathematical Symbols</title>

<para>&kile; enables you to directly insert the most current tags with
the <guimenu>Latex</guimenu> and <guimenu>Math</guimenu> menus. With a
simple click on a mathematical symbol, &kile; inserts the
corresponding code.</para>

<screenshot>
<screeninfo>Inserting Symbols</screeninfo>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject>
<imagedata fileref="doc5.png" format="PNG" />
</imageobject>
<textobject>
<phrase>Inserting Symbols</phrase>
</textobject>
<caption><para>Inserting Symbols</para></caption>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>

<para>
In addition to the many standard LaTeX tags you can insert into your document by selecting them in the LaTeX and Math menus, you can also define
your own tags. Tags you frequently use for example. The first twelve tags can be accessed via the keyboard shortcuts Shift+F1 to Shift+F12.
</para>

<note><para>If the code saved in the menu is
<quote>%environment</quote> then &kile; will directly insert:</para>
<screen><computeroutput>\begin{environment }
\end{environment }</computeroutput></screen>
</note>

<screenshot>
<screeninfo>A <guimenu>User</guimenu> Menu Entry</screeninfo>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject>
<imagedata fileref="doc6.png" format="PNG" />
</imageobject>
<textobject>
<phrase>A <guimenu>User</guimenu> Menu Entry</phrase>
</textobject>
<caption>
<para>A <guimenu>User</guimenu> Menu Entry</para>
</caption>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>

<para>
To edit the tags choose <guimenuitem>Edit User Tags</guimenuitem> from the <menuchoice><guimenu>User</guimenu><guimenu>User Tags</guimenu></menuchoice> menu. To add a tag, select the "Add" radiobutton and enter a short descriptive name for the tag and enter the tag itself. When you're done simply click on the Ok button. To change or remove a tag, select the tag from the drop-down menu and select the "Edit" or "Remove" radiobutton.
</para>

<para>For <quote>bib</quote> files, the
<guimenu>Bibliography</guimenu> menu enables you to directly insert
the entries corresponding to the standard types of document. Use the
<guimenuitem>Clean</guimenuitem> command to delete the optional
fields.</para>

<para>Selected text can be directly framed by certain
environments.</para>

<para>While clicking on the button <guiicon>Bold</guiicon> after
having selected the word <quote>Hello</quote> you will obtain the
code:</para>
<screen><computeroutput>\textbf{Hello}</computeroutput></screen>

<para><inlinemediaobject><imageobject> <imagedata fileref="doc7.png"
format="PNG" /></imageobject></inlinemediaobject><inlinemediaobject><imageobject> <imagedata fileref="doc8.png"
format="PNG" /></imageobject></inlinemediaobject></para>

<!-- This doesn't make a whole lot of sense... 
<para>This option is available for the environments of the "Font -->
<!-- Styles" and "Math Font Styles" menus like for the "center", -->
<!-- "flushleft", "flushright", "tiny", "scriptsize"... environments) -->
<!-- </para> -->

<para>The <guimenuitem>Tabular</guimenuitem>,
<guimenuitem>Array</guimenuitem> and
<guimenuitem>Tabbing</guimenuitem> wizards are at your disposal via
the <guimenu>Wizard</guimenu> menu, to help you insert the code
corresponding to these environments.</para>

<para>Spell checking of your document (or of the selected text) is
possible via the
<menuchoice><guimenu>Edit</guimenu><guimenuitem>Spelling...</guimenuitem></menuchoice>
menu item.</para>

</sect2>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="latex-shell">
<title>The LaTeX Shell</title>

<para>The commands in the <guimenu>Tools</guimenu> menu enable you to
directly launch the standard programs associated with LaTeX. To
configure these tools, use the
<menuchoice><guimenu>Options</guimenu><guimenuitem>Configure
Kile</guimenuitem></menuchoice> menu item.</para>

<sect2 id="log-file">
<title>About the Log File</title>

<para>The <guimenuitem>Next Latex Error</guimenuitem> and
<guimenuitem>Previous LaTeX Error</guimenuitem> commands allow to get
to the errors detected during compilation. While clicking on the
number of a line in the <filename>log</filename> file , the cursor is
placed on the corresponding line in the editor.</para>

