</para>
</sect2>

<sect2>
<title>Define your own tools</title>
<para>
If the standard tools Kile provides access to (e.g. latex, dvips, etc.) do not satisfy your needs, you can add define your own tools. Editing these tools is essentially the same as editing the user tags (see <link linkend="tags-and-math-symbols">LaTeX tags and Mathematical Symbols</link>). The shortcuts for the first twelve tools are Alt+Shift+F1 to Alt+Shift+F12.
</para>
<para>It is possible to pass the name of the current document to the user tool, this is done via the sequence <screen><computeroutput>%S</computeroutput></screen>. For example <screen><computeroutput>lpr %S.ps</computeroutput></screen> would print the file <screen><computeroutput>test.ps</computeroutput></screen> if the current document was <screen><computeroutput>test.tex</computeroutput></screen>.
</para>
</sect2>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="gnuplot-front-end">
<title>The &gnuplot; Front End</title>

<para>The &gnuplot; front end provided with &kile; is an adaptation of
the <application>Xgfe</application> program created by David Ishee.
The use of this tool requires experience of &gnuplot;.</para>

<!-- <example>
<title>Layout of the function <quote>sinus</quote> with
&gnuplot;</title>

<para></para>
-->

<procedure>
<step><para>Check the <guilabel>Function</guilabel> box and enter
<userinput>sin(x)</userinput> in the corresponding
field.</para></step>
<step><para>Enter <userinput>X</userinput> in the <guilabel>Variable
X</guilabel> field, <userinput>-5</userinput> in the
<guilabel>Start</guilabel> and <userinput>5</userinput> in the
<guilabel>End</guilabel> field.</para></step>
<step><para>Click on the <guibutton>Plot</guibutton> button to see the
graphic.</para></step>
<step><para>To export the graphic in the Xfig format, select
<guimenuitem>fig</guimenuitem> in the <guimenu>Terminal</guimenu>
menu, then click on the <guibutton>Output File</guibutton> button, and
enter the name of the file with the extension <literal
role="extension">.fig</literal>.  Then click the
<guibutton>Plot</guibutton>.  You may now open this graphic with
<application>Xfig</application> to modify it, and export it with the
<literal role="extension">eps</literal> format before incorporating it
into your document.</para>
</step></procedure>

